{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}
The '''Bocholt disaster''' refers to the collapse of Spinnerei Beckmann cotton mill, in [[Bocholt, Germany|Bocholt]], [[Germany]], shortly before its completion in 1895. Franz Beckmann, through the offices of [[Platt Brothers]] of [[Oldham]], had commissioned [[Sir Philip Stott, 1st Baronet|Sydney Stott]] to draw up plans for a [[mule spinning]] mill. The foundations were faulty and the mill collapsed on 18 October 1895. There were 22 men killed.

